00:21:45,120 --> 00:21:49,000 
If someone scratches their nose,
experts tell you it means they're lying.

251
00:21:49,120 --> 00:21:52,480 
It really means they're nervous. People
get nervous for all sorts of reasons.

252
00:21:52,600 --> 00:21:53,680 
It's all about context.

253
00:21:53,800 --> 00:21:55,680 
Yeah, I was good.

254
00:21:55,800 --> 00:21:58,680 
Sammy was my first real challenge.

255
00:22:00,200 --> 00:22:01,880 
(engine starts)

256
00:22:05,000 --> 00:22:08,120 
Yo, Lenny! I thought you'd split for good.

257
00:22:08,200 --> 00:22:10,480 
- Well, things change.
- So I see.

258
00:22:10,600 --> 00:22:13,520 
- My name's Teddy.
- I guess I've told you about my condition.

259
00:22:13,600 --> 00:22:17,400 
Only every time I see ya.
Come on, I'll buy you lunch.

260
00:22:22,800 --> 00:22:25,000 
- Have I told you about Sammy Jankis?
- Mmm. Yeah.

261
00:22:25,120 --> 00:22:27,000 
I'm sick of hearing about the guy.

262
00:22:27,120 --> 00:22:29,200 
What about John G?
You think he's still here?

263
00:22:29,320 --> 00:22:31,800 
- Who?
- Johnny G, the guy you're looking for.

264
00:22:31,880 --> 00:22:34,200 
- That's why you haven't left town, right?
- Maybe.

265
00:22:34,320 --> 00:22:37,520 
- Leonard, you have to be very careful.
- Why?

266
00:22:37,600 --> 00:22:40,480 
You mentioned that maybe somebody
was trying to set you up.

267
00:22:40,600 --> 00:22:42,120 
Get you to kill the wrong guy.

268
00:22:42,200 --> 00:22:45,600 
I go on facts, not recommendations,
but thank you.

269
00:22:45,680 --> 00:22:48,600 
Lenny, you can't trust a man's life
to your little notes and pictures.

270
00:22:48,680 --> 00:22:51,400 
- Why not?
- Because your notes could be unreliable.

271
00:22:51,520 --> 00:22:53,120 
- Memory's unreliable.
- Oh, please.

272
00:22:53,200 --> 00:22:56,680 
No, really. Memory's not perfect,
it's not even that good. Ask the police.

273
00:22:56,800 --> 00:22:59,120 
Eyewitness testimony is unreliable.

274
00:22:59,200 --> 00:23:01,600 
The cops don't catch a killer
by sitting around remembering stuff.

275
00:23:01,680 --> 00:23:04,480 
- They collect facts and draw conclusions.
- That's not what I'm saying.

276
00:23:04,600 --> 00:23:06,680 
Facts, not memories.

277
00:23:06,800 --> 00:23:09,000 
That's how you investigate.
I know, it's what I used to do.

278
00:23:09,120 --> 00:23:12,880 
Memory can change the shape of a room,
it can change the color of a car.

279
00:23:13,200 --> 00:23:15,320 
And memories can be distorted.

280
00:23:15,400 --> 00:23:17,320 
They're an interpretation, not a record.

281
00:23:17,400 --> 00:23:19,400 
They're irrelevant if you have the facts.

282
00:23:19,520 --> 00:23:22,400 
You really want to get this guy, don't you?

283
00:23:22,480 --> 00:23:25,880 
He killed my wife.
He took away my fucking memory.

284
00:23:27,680 --> 00:23:30,200 
He destroyed my ability to live.

285
00:23:33,000 --> 00:23:34,320 
You're living.

286
00:23:35,320 --> 00:23:37,000 
Only for revenge.

287
00:23:37,400 --> 00:23:39,320 
Well, then we'll get the bastard.

288
00:23:39,400 --> 00:23:41,520 
Where are you staying?

289
00:23:44,000 --> 00:23:48,200 
The Discount Inn. I don't know what room.
I haven't got my key.

290
00:23:48,320 --> 00:23:50,400 
Probably left it in your room.

291
00:24:01,520 --> 00:24:02,480 
(rings bell)

292
00:24:03,880 --> 00:24:05,000 
Hi.

293
00:24:05,120 --> 00:24:07,200 
I'm checked in here
but I think I've misplaced my key.

294
00:24:07,320 --> 00:24:11,400 
How you doing, Leonard?
Probably in the room, right?

295
00:24:29,320 --> 00:24:31,680 
- I don't see my key anywhere.
- Oh, shit. This is the wrong room.

296
00:24:31,800 --> 00:24:33,600 
You're in 304. I'm sorry. I fucked up.

297
00:24:33,680 --> 00:24:36,400 
- This is not my room?
- No. Come on, let's go.

298
00:24:36,480 --> 00:24:38,320 
Then why is this my handwriting?

299
00:24:42,000 --> 00:24:46,120 
Well,... this was your room
but now you're in 304.

300
00:24:46,200 --> 00:24:48,320 
- When was I in here?
- Last week.

301
00:24:48,400 --> 00:24:51,680 
- Then I rented you another room on top.
- Why?

302
00:24:51,800 --> 00:24:56,200 
Business is slow, I mean, I told my boss
about your condition and stuff,...

303
00:24:56,320 --> 00:24:57,880 
..he said rent him another room.

304
00:24:58,000 --> 00:25:00,120 
So how many rooms am I checked into
in this shit hole?

305
00:25:00,200 --> 00:25:02,600 
Just two. So far.

306
00:25:02,680 --> 00:25:03,400 
Well,...

307
00:25:03,520 --> 00:25:06,000 
..at least you're being honest
about ripping me off.

308
00:25:06,120 --> 00:25:10,480 
- You're not going to remember anyway.
- You don't have to be that honest, Burt.

309
00:25:10,600 --> 00:25:13,200 
Leonard. Always get a receipt.

310
00:25:14,000 --> 00:25:16,200 
Oh, yeah. I'll write that down.

311
00:25:18,200 --> 00:25:21,400 
- Hey, what time is it?
- Quarter to one.

312
00:25:21,680 --> 00:25:23,520 
Excuse me.

313
00:25:23,600 --> 00:25:25,120 
Your room's...

314
00:25:37,400 --> 00:25:39,320 
- Natalie.
- You don't remember me.

315
00:25:39,680 --> 00:25:42,480 
I'd just become an investigator
when I came across Sammy.

316
00:25:42,600 --> 00:25:46,120 
Mr. Samuel R Jankis, strangest case ever.

317
00:25:46,200 --> 00:25:49,200 
The guy's a 58-year-old,
semi-retired accountant.

318
00:25:49,320 --> 00:25:51,520 
He and his wife were in this car accident,
nothing serious.

319
00:25:51,600 --> 00:25:54,600 
But he's acting funny,
he can't get a handle on what's going on.

320
00:25:56,120 --> 00:25:59,600 
The doctors find some possible damage
to the hippocampus, nothing conclusive.

321
00:25:59,680 --> 00:26:03,200 
Sammy can't remember anything
for more than a couple of minutes.

322
00:26:03,320 --> 00:26:04,600 
Can't work, can't do shit.

323
00:26:04,680 --> 00:26:07,800 
The medical bills pile up, his wife calls
the insurance company and I get sent in.

324
00:26:09,000 --> 00:26:13,880 
This is my first big claims investigation
so I really check into it.

325
00:26:14,000 --> 00:26:17,520 
Sammy can think just fine
but he can't make new memories.

326
00:26:17,600 --> 00:26:20,120 
He can only remember things
for a couple of minutes.

327
00:26:21,680 --> 00:26:24,800 
He'd watch TV but anything longer than
a couple of minutes was too confusing,...

328
00:26:24,880 --> 00:26:26,880 
..he couldn't remember how it began.

329
00:26:27,000 --> 00:26:29,200 
He liked commercials. They were short.

330
00:26:29,320 --> 00:26:31,120 
Sammy. It's time for my shot.

331
00:26:31,200 --> 00:26:34,120 
The crazy part was that this guy,...

332
00:26:34,200 --> 00:26:36,600 
..who couldn't follow
the plot of Green Acres any more,...

333
00:26:36,680 --> 00:26:38,680 
..could do the most complicated things,...

334
00:26:38,800 --> 00:26:40,880 
..as long as he learned them
before the accident...

335
00:26:43,320 --> 00:26:45,520 
..and as long as he kept his mind
on what he was doing.

336
00:26:46,400 --> 00:26:49,200 
The doctors assure me...

337
00:26:49,320 --> 00:26:53,400 
..there's a real condition, anterial-grade
memory loss, or short-term memory loss.

338
00:26:53,520 --> 00:26:55,400 
It's rare but legit.

339
00:26:56,800 --> 00:26:59,400 
But every time I see him,...

340
00:26:59,600 --> 00:27:01,800 
..I catch this look,...

341
00:27:02,200 --> 00:27:05,120 
..this... slight look of recognition.

342
00:27:05,600 --> 00:27:07,880 
But he says he can't remember me at all.

343
00:27:08,480 --> 00:27:10,480 
Sammy, it's OK. I got it.

344
00:27:10,800 --> 00:27:13,120 
- Hi, Mr. Shelby.
- Hi, Mrs. Jankis.

345
00:27:13,200 --> 00:27:17,320 
Now, I can read people
and I'm thinking ''bad actor''.

346
00:27:17,400 --> 00:27:20,000 
So now I'm suspicious
and I order more tests.

347
00:27:23,320 --> 00:27:25,320 
Awake.

348
00:27:26,480 --> 00:27:29,120 
Oh, where am I?

349
00:27:31,400 --> 00:27:33,520 
Somebody's bedroom.

350
00:27:35,320 --> 00:27:37,520 
Oh, it must be her room.

351
00:27:38,400 --> 00:27:40,400 
But who is she?

352
00:27:48,000 --> 00:27:49,800 
It's only me.

353
00:27:51,880 --> 00:27:54,880 
- Did you sleep OK?
- Yeah. You?

354
00:27:56,400 --> 00:27:58,320 
Oh, shit. Shit.

355
00:27:58,400 --> 00:28:00,120 
I gotta be someplace.

356
00:28:03,800 --> 00:28:05,200 
It's pretty weird.

357
00:28:06,200 --> 00:28:09,800 
It's useful. You never
write a phone number on your hand?

358
00:28:09,880 --> 00:28:14,000 
I, um, I should be able
to talk to my friend today...

359
00:28:14,120 --> 00:28:17,120 
- ..about the license plate.
- Yeah, the license plate.

360
00:28:17,200 --> 00:28:19,520 
John G's license plate.

361
00:28:22,200 --> 00:28:24,200 
You have it tattooed on your thigh.

362
00:28:41,800 --> 00:28:43,680 
Natalie.

363
00:28:45,800 --> 00:28:49,520 
She has also lost someone.
She will help you out of pity.

364
00:28:54,600 --> 00:28:56,480 
If it's registered in this state,...

365
00:28:56,600 --> 00:28:58,680 
..it should only take a couple seconds
to pull up his license and registration.

366
00:28:58,800 --> 00:29:01,200 
I'll call you as soon as I talk to him.

367
00:29:01,320 --> 00:29:04,120 
Could we arrange a meeting now?
I'm not too good on the phone.

368
00:29:13,120 --> 00:29:15,200 
You know, it's great that you...

369
00:29:15,400 --> 00:29:17,200 
Well, that you're...

370
00:29:17,520 --> 00:29:19,000 
..helping me...

371
00:29:19,320 --> 00:29:20,600 
..like this.

372
00:29:20,680 --> 00:29:23,880 
I'm helping you because you helped me.

373
00:29:35,600 --> 00:29:37,880 
So next time you see me,...

374
00:29:38,000 --> 00:29:39,400 
..will you remember me?

375
00:29:55,680 --> 00:29:57,880 
(softly) I think you will.

376
00:29:59,000 --> 00:30:00,880 
(softly) I'm sorry.

377
00:30:03,200 --> 00:30:06,600 
Lenny, before you go,
could I have my shirt back, please?

378
00:30:17,800 --> 00:30:19,680 
(engine starts)

379
00:30:22,320 --> 00:30:25,120 
Yo, Lenny! I thought you'd split for good.

380
00:30:25,400 --> 00:30:28,120 
Sammy couldn't pick up
any new skills at all.

381
00:30:28,200 --> 00:30:30,480 
But I find something in my research.

382
00:30:30,600 --> 00:30:32,120 
Conditioning.

383
00:30:32,200 --> 00:30:35,000 
Sammy should still be able to learn
through repetition.

384
00:30:35,120 --> 00:30:38,320 
It's how you learn stuff like riding a bike.
You get better through practice.

385
00:30:38,400 --> 00:30:40,480 
It's a different part of the brain
from the short-term memory.

386
00:30:40,600 --> 00:30:44,000 
So I had the doctors
test Sammy's response to conditioning.

387
00:30:44,120 --> 00:30:48,120 
- Pick up any three objects.
- That's a test?

388
00:30:48,200 --> 00:30:50,400 
Where were you guys when I did my CPA?

389
00:30:50,480 --> 00:30:51,880 
Sorry.

390
00:30:54,000 --> 00:30:55,320 
Ta-da!

391
00:30:56,000 --> 00:30:58,120 
- (buzz)
- Ow! What the fuck?

392
00:30:58,200 --> 00:31:00,480 
- It's a test, Sammy.
- Test this, you fucking quack.

393
00:31:03,120 --> 00:31:06,120 
Some of the objects were electrified.
They'd give him a shock.

394
00:31:06,200 --> 00:31:09,120 
They kept repeating the test,
always with the same objects electrified.

395
00:31:09,200 --> 00:31:12,480 
The point was to see if Sammy could
learn to avoid the electrified objects,...

396
00:31:12,600 --> 00:31:14,800 
..not by memory, but by instinct.

397
00:31:23,320 --> 00:31:25,320 
(activates alarm)

398
00:31:29,520 --> 00:31:31,520 
(knocks on door)

399
00:31:34,680 --> 00:31:37,200 
Natalie, right? Who the fuck is Dodd?

400
00:31:39,600 --> 00:31:42,200 
Guess I don't have to worry about him
any more.

401
00:31:42,320 --> 00:31:44,120 
- What the fuck have you got me into?
- Shh. Come inside.

402
00:31:48,320 --> 00:31:51,120 
- Who is he?
- Calm down. OK?

403
00:31:51,200 --> 00:31:54,480 
This is my problem. You offered to help.
It's nothing to do with your investigation.

404
00:31:54,600 --> 00:31:56,120 
How did you get me into this?

405
00:31:56,200 --> 00:31:58,120 
You offered to help me
when you saw what he did to my face.

406
00:31:58,200 --> 00:32:01,600 
- How do I know he did that to your face?
- I came straight to you after he did it.

407
00:32:01,680 --> 00:32:03,880 
I showed you what he did
and I asked you to help me.

408
00:32:04,000 --> 00:32:06,680 
- Oh, and I just take your word?
- Yeah.

409
00:32:07,120 --> 00:32:09,320 
Something doesn't feel right.

410
00:32:09,400 --> 00:32:11,680 
I think someone's fucking with me,
trying to get me to kill the wrong guy.

411
00:32:11,800 --> 00:32:13,000 
- Did you?
- What?

412
00:32:13,120 --> 00:32:14,880 
Kill him?

413
00:32:15,000 --> 00:32:18,320 
- Course not!
- Hey. Sit down, OK? Sit.

414
00:32:19,000 --> 00:32:23,680 
This has nothing to do with you.
You helped me out and I'm grateful.

415
00:32:24,400 --> 00:32:26,120 
You have to burn them.

416
00:32:29,520 --> 00:32:33,320 
Leonard, you decided to help me.
Trust your own judgment.

417
00:32:33,400 --> 00:32:36,680 
You can question everything,
you can never know anything for sure.

418
00:32:36,800 --> 00:32:39,400 
- There are things you know for sure.
- Such as?

419
00:32:40,320 --> 00:32:43,880 
I know what that's gonna sound like
when I knock on it. (knocks)

420
00:32:44,000 --> 00:32:47,200 
I know what that's gonna feel like
when I pick it up. See?

421
00:32:47,320 --> 00:32:50,000 
Certainties. It's the kind of memory
you take for granted.

422
00:32:51,520 --> 00:32:54,320 
You know, I can remember so much.

423
00:32:55,400 --> 00:32:57,320 
The feel of the world...

424
00:32:57,800 --> 00:32:59,800 
And her.

425
00:33:05,400 --> 00:33:07,320 
She's gone.

426
00:33:07,400 --> 00:33:11,120 
And the present is trivia
which I scribble down as fucking notes.

427
00:33:11,200 --> 00:33:13,800 
Hey, come on. Try and relax. Come on.

428
00:33:13,880 --> 00:33:16,800 
- It's not easy for me to relax.
- Shh. Shhh.

429
00:33:17,120 --> 00:33:19,200 
Come on, take your jacket off.

430
00:33:19,320 --> 00:33:21,520 
(softly) Here. Come on.

431
00:33:22,880 --> 00:33:24,680 
(softly) Hey.

432
00:33:25,000 --> 00:33:26,880 
Didn't think you were the type.

433
00:33:35,880 --> 00:33:37,880 
It's backwards.

434
00:33:38,800 --> 00:33:41,400 
Come here. Come here.

435
00:34:02,120 --> 00:34:04,120 
What about here?

436
00:34:05,600 --> 00:34:07,880 
Maybe it's... for when I find him.

437
00:34:10,400 --> 00:34:13,000 
I've lost somebody too.

438
00:34:14,200 --> 00:34:16,200 
I'm sorry.

439
00:34:16,320 --> 00:34:18,120 
His name was Jimmy.

440
00:34:18,200 --> 00:34:20,480 
- What happened to him?
- He went to meet somebody.

441
00:34:21,320 --> 00:34:23,400 
He never came back.

442
00:34:24,400 --> 00:34:27,320 
- Who did he go to meet?
- A guy called Teddy.

443
00:34:28,200 --> 00:34:30,120 
What do the police think?

444
00:34:30,400 --> 00:34:34,000 
They don't look too hard
for guys like Jimmy.

445
00:34:34,600 --> 00:34:37,200 
When you find this guy, this...

446
00:34:37,320 --> 00:34:40,400 
..John G, what are you gonna do?

447
00:34:42,680 --> 00:34:44,680 
I'm gonna kill him.

448
00:34:46,400 --> 00:34:49,120 
Maybe I can help you find him.

449
00:34:53,000 --> 00:34:56,600 
I don't even know how long
she's been gone.

450
00:34:59,600 --> 00:35:03,120 
It's like I've woken up in bed
and she's not here...

451
00:35:04,800 --> 00:35:08,800 
..because she's gone to the bathroom
or something.

452
00:35:11,880 --> 00:35:14,320 
But somehow I just...

453
00:35:15,000 --> 00:35:19,120 
I just know
she's never gonna come back to bed.

454
00:35:23,000 --> 00:35:24,880 
If I could just...

455
00:35:25,320 --> 00:35:28,880 
..reach over
and touch her side of the bed,...

456
00:35:30,200 --> 00:35:32,800 
..I would know that it was cold.

457
00:35:35,000 --> 00:35:37,120 
But I can't.

458
00:35:40,680 --> 00:35:42,600 
I know I can't have her back.

459
00:35:44,480 --> 00:35:49,120 
But I don't want to wake up in the morning
thinking she's still here.

460
00:35:49,600 --> 00:35:53,880 
I lie here not knowing
how long I've been alone.

461
00:35:59,600 --> 00:36:01,520 
So how...

462
00:36:02,120 --> 00:36:04,120 
How can I heal?

463
00:36:06,480 --> 00:36:09,520 
How am I supposed to heal if I can't...

464
00:36:10,320 --> 00:36:12,320 
..feel time?

465
00:37:21,520 --> 00:37:26,000 
She has also lost someone.
She will help you out of pity.

466
00:37:50,120 --> 00:37:52,800 
They kept testing Sammy for months.

467
00:37:52,880 --> 00:37:55,680 
Always with the same objects
carrying the electrical charge.

468
00:37:55,800 --> 00:37:57,800 
- (buzz)
- Ow! What the fuck?

469
00:37:57,880 --> 00:38:00,200 
- It's a test, Sammy.
- Test this, you fucking quack!

470
00:38:00,320 --> 00:38:02,320 
Even with total short-term memory loss,...

471
00:38:02,400 --> 00:38:05,600 
..Sammy should have learned instinctively
to stop picking up the wrong objects.

472
00:38:05,680 --> 00:38:09,520 
Other cases responded to conditioning,
Sammy didn't respond at all.

473
00:38:09,600 --> 00:38:13,120 
It suggested that his condition
was psychological not physical.

474
00:38:13,200 --> 00:38:17,520 
We turned down his claim on the grounds
that he wasn't covered for mental illness.

475
00:38:17,600 --> 00:38:20,880 
His wife got stuck with the bills
and I got a big promotion.

476
00:38:21,600 --> 00:38:25,400 
Conditioning didn't work for Sammy,
so he became helpless.

477
00:38:25,520 --> 00:38:27,400 
But it works for me.

478
00:38:27,520 --> 00:38:29,520 
I live the way Sammy couldn't.

479
00:38:29,600 --> 00:38:32,000 
Habit and routine make my life possible.

480
00:38:32,120 --> 00:38:34,680 
Conditioning. Acting on instinct.

481
00:38:36,800 --> 00:38:39,680 
(muffled cries)

482
00:38:41,680 --> 00:38:42,480 
(smash)

483
00:38:43,400 --> 00:38:45,320 
Awake.

484
00:38:45,600 --> 00:38:47,520 
Where am I?

485
00:38:49,000 --> 00:38:50,880 
Motel room.

486
00:38:51,400 --> 00:38:53,320 
Oh.

487
00:38:56,880 --> 00:38:59,600 
Some anonymous motel room.

488
00:39:03,000 --> 00:39:06,320 
Nothing in the drawers.
But I'll take a look anyway.

489
00:39:06,400 --> 00:39:08,400 
Nothing except the Gideon Bi...

490
00:39:08,480 --> 00:39:10,320 
Bible.

491
00:39:22,800 --> 00:39:25,000 
- (knock on door)
- Hey! Open up!

492
00:39:26,320 --> 00:39:28,320 
- (muffled cries)
- Just a minute!

493
00:39:28,400 --> 00:39:30,120 
Open the door!

494
00:39:31,000 --> 00:39:33,600 
- (muffled cries)
- (knocks) Lenny?

495
00:39:34,400 --> 00:39:37,320 
(knocking continues) Open the door!

496
00:39:41,400 --> 00:39:43,320 
Come on!

497
00:39:45,000 --> 00:39:48,320 
- Hi, Teddy.
- Finished playing with yourself, Lenny?

498
00:39:48,800 --> 00:39:51,680 
- Oh!
- (muffled cries)

499
00:39:56,000 --> 00:39:57,880 
(sighs)

500
00:39:59,400 --> 00:40:01,880 
- (muffled cries)
- Oh, I get it.

501
00:40:02,680 --> 00:40:05,120 
- Amorous neighbors.
- What are you doing here?

502
00:40:05,200 --> 00:40:08,680 
(laughs) You called me.
You said you needed my help.

503
00:40:08,800 --> 00:40:12,120 
You know, I've had more
rewarding friendships than this one.

504
00:40:12,200 --> 00:40:15,520 
Although I do get to keep telling
the same jokes.

505
00:40:15,600 --> 00:40:17,200 
What the fuck is that?

506
00:40:23,400 --> 00:40:24,800 
Who the fuck is that?

507
00:40:24,880 --> 00:40:26,880 
- You don't know him?
- No! Should I?

508
00:40:27,120 --> 00:40:31,000 
- Wait a minute. Is that John G?
- I don't think so.

509
00:40:31,120 --> 00:40:33,120 
You don't think so?
You didn't write it down?

510
00:40:33,200 --> 00:40:36,320 
- I might have fallen asleep before I did.
- For Christ sakes!

511
00:40:37,400 --> 00:40:39,320 
Ask him.

512
00:40:42,800 --> 00:40:45,400 
What's your name? Your name?

513
00:40:45,800 --> 00:40:47,680 
- Dodd.
- And who did this to you?

514
00:40:47,800 --> 00:40:49,800 
- What?
- Who did this to you?

515
00:40:50,400 --> 00:40:52,400 
You did.

516
00:40:54,320 --> 00:40:58,120 
- I'm not going to help you kill that guy.
- No, no. Just let me think for a minute.

517
00:41:01,320 --> 00:41:03,320 
(muffled cries)

518
00:41:03,600 --> 00:41:06,480 
OK, Natalie. Who's Natalie? Natalie who?

519
00:41:06,600 --> 00:41:08,680 
- Why?
- Maybe I know her.

520
00:41:08,800 --> 00:41:11,320 
Look, we gotta get him out of here.

521
00:41:11,400 --> 00:41:13,320 
All right, all right, all right.

522
00:41:14,200 --> 00:41:16,200 
He's got to have a car, right?

523
00:41:16,320 --> 00:41:19,400 
We take him to his car, tell him to get the
fuck out of town or we're gonna kill him.

524
00:41:19,520 --> 00:41:21,520 
We can't walk him out of here
tied up and bleeding.

525
00:41:21,600 --> 00:41:23,880 
- How the fuck did you get him up here?
- I don't know!

526
00:41:24,000 --> 00:41:26,320 
- You don't know.
- (muffled banging)

527
00:41:27,600 --> 00:41:31,320 
Yes, I do. This is not my room.
It must be his room. Great. Let's go.

528
00:41:31,400 --> 00:41:33,400 
- No, no, no. We can't just leave him here.
- Why not?

529
00:41:33,520 --> 00:41:38,400 
Because the maid's gonna walk in.
She'll see him, call the cops. He can ID us.

530
00:41:39,600 --> 00:41:42,320 
OK. We untie him, we clean him up...

531
00:41:42,400 --> 00:41:44,400 
..and we march him out of here
with a gun in his back.

532
00:41:44,480 --> 00:41:46,480 
A gun. Why would I have a gun?

533
00:41:47,600 --> 00:41:51,600 
It must be his. I don't think
they'd let someone like me carry a gun.

534
00:41:51,880 --> 00:41:53,680 
Fucking hope not.

535
00:42:00,800 --> 00:42:02,680 
Which one?

536
00:42:05,200 --> 00:42:07,680 
We should probably steal his car.
You know, teach him a lesson.

537
00:42:07,800 --> 00:42:10,600 
- Shut up.
- It's all right for you, you've got the Jag.

538
00:42:10,680 --> 00:42:13,680 
All right, get in.
I'm gonna ride with him, you follow us.

539
00:42:13,800 --> 00:42:15,680 
Give me your keys.

540
00:42:15,800 --> 00:42:17,680 
Take your own car.

541
00:42:43,680 --> 00:42:45,680 
So was he scared?

542
00:42:45,800 --> 00:42:47,600 
I think it was your sinister moustache.

543
00:42:47,680 --> 00:42:50,400 
Fuck you. Should have stolen his car.

544
00:42:50,480 --> 00:42:54,320 
- Why? What's wrong with this one?
- Nothing. You want to trade?

545
00:42:56,480 --> 00:42:58,480 
So what do you do now?

546
00:42:58,600 --> 00:43:01,600 
I'm gonna find out
what the fuck that was all about.

547
00:43:04,880 --> 00:43:06,800 
(knocks)

548
00:43:08,000 --> 00:43:10,480 
Natalie, right? Who the fuck is Dodd?

549
00:43:12,600 --> 00:43:15,880 
Sammy's wife was crippled
by the cost of supporting him.

550
00:43:16,000 --> 00:43:19,000 
And fighting the company's decision.

551
00:43:19,520 --> 00:43:22,000 
But it wasn't the money that got to her.

552
00:43:22,120 --> 00:43:24,480 
I never said that Sammy was faking.

553
00:43:24,600 --> 00:43:26,480 
Sammy, I have an idea.

554
00:43:26,600 --> 00:43:29,800 
Just that his problem was mental,
not physical.

555
00:43:29,880 --> 00:43:32,480 
You're gonna have a pen in your pocket.

556
00:43:32,600 --> 00:43:34,320 
She couldn't understand.

557
00:43:34,400 --> 00:43:36,880 
- I did something wrong?
- You did something wrong!

558
00:43:37,000 --> 00:43:40,200 
We're gonna deal with it.
We're gonna try a little harder.

559
00:43:40,320 --> 00:43:43,120 
She looks into his eyes
and sees the same person...

560
00:43:43,200 --> 00:43:45,680 
..and if it's not a physical problem,
he should snap out of it.

561
00:43:45,800 --> 00:43:46,800 
- Ellen called!
- Ellen called.

562
00:43:46,880 --> 00:43:49,680 
Ellen called.
Ellen... Ellen can't come today!

563
00:43:49,800 --> 00:43:52,320 
- Ellen can't come!
- I'm so sorry! I'm sorry!

564
00:43:52,400 --> 00:43:54,600 
- I'm trying! I'm sorry!
- (sobs)

565
00:43:57,520 --> 00:44:02,120 
So, Leonard Shelby from the insurance
company gives her the seed of doubt.

566
00:44:02,200 --> 00:44:04,680 
Just like he gave it to the doctors.

567
00:44:04,800 --> 00:44:07,120 
But I never said that he was faking.

568
00:44:07,200 --> 00:44:09,120 
I never said that.

569
00:44:13,680 --> 00:44:16,320 
Hmm. I don't feel drunk.

570
00:44:47,400 --> 00:44:48,880 
(door closes)

571
00:44:58,120 --> 00:45:00,120 
(toilet flushes)

572
00:45:25,680 --> 00:45:27,600 
- Hello? Housekeeping.
- Oh, shit!

573
00:45:28,400 --> 00:45:31,320 
- Not right now!
- Oh, I'm sorry.

574
00:45:58,200 --> 00:46:03,120 
Dodd. Put him onto Teddy
or just get rid of him for Natalie.

575
00:46:07,800 --> 00:46:09,680 
Dodd.

576
00:46:14,200 --> 00:46:17,400 
Get rid of him. Ask Natalie.

577
00:46:19,120 --> 00:46:20,800 
Teddy, Teddy.

578
00:46:23,000 --> 00:46:24,880 
(dialing tone)

579
00:46:26,600 --> 00:46:28,480 
(ringing)

580
00:46:31,000 --> 00:46:33,120 
Yeah, leave your number,
you know what to do.

581
00:46:33,200 --> 00:46:36,120 
- (beep)
- Yeah. This is a message for Teddy.

582
00:46:36,200 --> 00:46:38,320 
I'm at the Mount Crest Inn on Fifth Street,
room six.

583
00:46:38,400 --> 00:46:41,120 
I need you to come over
as soon as you get this. It's important.

584
00:46:41,200 --> 00:46:43,320 
Oh, this is Leonard. Thanks. Bye.

585
00:46:45,520 --> 00:46:47,320 
Phew!

586
00:46:47,600 --> 00:46:49,320 
Fuck!

587
00:46:57,400 --> 00:47:01,400 
Mrs. Jankis didn't understand that you
can't bully someone into remembering.

588
00:47:01,520 --> 00:47:04,400 
The more pressure you're under,
the harder it gets.

589
00:47:05,000 --> 00:47:08,120 
Ah. Well, then, call me back?

590
00:47:23,600 --> 00:47:25,520 
(car alarm, car horn)

591
00:47:28,800 --> 00:47:30,680 
OK. So what am I doing?

592
00:47:33,000 --> 00:47:34,480 
Oh, I'm chasing this guy.

593
00:47:37,000 --> 00:47:39,800 
No. He's chasing me.

594
00:47:43,000 --> 00:47:45,200 
(car alarm, car horn)

595
00:47:47,400 --> 00:47:49,320 
(clicks off alarm)

596
00:47:58,320 --> 00:47:59,680 
(tires squeal)

597
00:48:00,320 --> 00:48:02,320 
Ah! Fuck!

598
00:48:06,320 --> 00:48:10,000 
Dodd, white guy,
Mount Crest Inn on Fifth Street.

599
00:48:11,400 --> 00:48:13,120 
I'll get the jump on you, you fucker.

600
00:48:49,200 --> 00:48:51,120 
Oh, fuck!

601
00:48:52,200 --> 00:48:54,200 
Sorry.

602
00:49:26,320 --> 00:49:28,200 
I need a weapon.

603
00:49:31,400 --> 00:49:32,480 
This'll do.

604
00:49:55,320 --> 00:49:57,600 
Hmm. I don't feel drunk.

605
00:50:26,480 --> 00:50:28,400 
(clicks off alarm)

606
00:50:32,880 --> 00:50:34,800 
(car horn)

607
00:50:35,200 --> 00:50:37,200 
(car horn)

608
00:50:37,400 --> 00:50:39,400 
Do I know this guy?

609
00:50:40,200 --> 00:50:42,320 
- (car horn)
- He seems to know me.

610
00:50:47,000 --> 00:50:48,880 
- What the fuck?
- (tires squeal)

611
00:51:01,120 --> 00:51:03,400 
- I like your car.
- Thank you.

612
00:51:03,520 --> 00:51:05,400 
- Where'd you get it?
- Are you interested in buying one?

613
00:51:05,520 --> 00:51:07,880 
What, I haven't made
a strong enough impression on you?

614
00:51:08,000 --> 00:51:10,480 
- I wouldn't be too hard on yourself.
- (taps on window)

615
00:51:15,000 --> 00:51:17,120 
(car alarm, car horn)

616
00:51:20,200 --> 00:51:22,320 
OK. So what am I doing?

617
00:51:29,600 --> 00:51:31,520 
(phone rings)

618
00:51:32,320 --> 00:51:34,200 
Who is this?

619
00:51:37,880 --> 00:51:39,880 
(clicks off alarm)

620
00:52:15,520 --> 00:52:17,400 
(activates car alarm)

621
00:52:49,320 --> 00:52:52,120 
Ouch! Cut it out.

622
00:53:21,600 --> 00:53:24,600 
- How can you read that again?
- It's good.

623
00:53:24,680 --> 00:53:29,200 
- You've read it, like, a thousand times.
- I enjoy it.

624
00:53:29,320 --> 00:53:33,120 
I thought the pleasure of a book was
in wanting to know what happens next.

625
00:53:33,200 --> 00:53:36,480 
Don't be a prick.
I'm not reading it to annoy you. I enjoy it.

626
00:53:38,400 --> 00:53:40,880 
Just let me read. Please?

627
00:53:51,320 --> 00:53:53,520 
Probably tried this before.

628
00:53:55,600 --> 00:53:58,680 
Probably burned truckloads of your stuff.

629
00:54:00,600 --> 00:54:03,200 
Can't remember to forget you.

630
00:54:19,880 --> 00:54:21,200 
Yeah.

631
00:54:21,320 --> 00:54:23,320 
Uh-huh.

632
00:54:23,400 --> 00:54:28,400 
Well, sir, that'd certainly be in keeping
with some of my own discoveries.

633
00:54:28,480 --> 00:54:31,520 
I was hoping for more on the drugs angle.
Will you hang on a sec?

634
00:54:40,200 --> 00:54:42,880 
The police report mentioned the drugs
found in the car outside my house.

635
00:54:43,000 --> 00:54:44,880 
The car was stolen.
His prints were all over it.

636
00:54:45,000 --> 00:54:47,000 
I got friends in the department.
They gave me a copy.

637
00:54:47,120 --> 00:54:48,880 
I dealt with the police a lot
in my insurance job.

638
00:54:49,000 --> 00:54:54,400 
With my condition it's really tough.
I can't keep it all in mind at once.

639
00:54:54,480 --> 00:54:56,120 
I have to summaries the sections.

640
00:54:56,200 --> 00:54:59,320 
There are pages missing.
I guess I've been trying to log them all.

641
00:54:59,400 --> 00:55:01,520 
I don't know why these are crossed out.

642
00:55:01,600 --> 00:55:03,600 
They weren't even looking for John G.

643
00:55:03,680 --> 00:55:06,320 
The stuff they found in the car fit in with
what they believed had happened,...

644
00:55:06,400 --> 00:55:08,480 
..so they didn't chase it up.

645
00:55:09,600 --> 00:55:11,520 
(door slams)

646
00:55:42,400 --> 00:55:43,680 
Honey?

647
00:55:46,120 --> 00:55:48,120 
Honey, it's late.

648
00:56:09,120 --> 00:56:11,000 
Everything OK?

649
00:56:11,400 --> 00:56:12,680 
(muffled cry)

650
00:56:22,120 --> 00:56:23,800 
(taps on door)

651
00:56:26,680 --> 00:56:29,120 
- (muffled gasp)
- You OK in there?

652
00:56:31,880 --> 00:56:34,320 
(sniffs) Was it good for you?

653
00:56:34,400 --> 00:56:36,400 
(laughs softly)

654
00:56:36,480 --> 00:56:39,200 
What? Was I supposed to lock the door?

655
00:56:40,400 --> 00:56:42,120 
(softly) No.

656
00:56:43,400 --> 00:56:45,320 
I'd like you to leave now.

657
00:56:55,680 --> 00:56:57,680 
(clicks off alarm)

658
00:57:05,000 --> 00:57:08,400 
There's something about the drugs
stashed in the car that doesn't ring true.

659
00:57:08,480 --> 00:57:12,480 
The police claim the guy was an addict
needing money to score. It's bullshit.

660
00:57:12,600 --> 00:57:16,800 
He's not gonna go breaking into places
while he's still got a stash that big.

661
00:57:17,120 --> 00:57:19,520 
Well, I think John G left it there.
Or planted it there.

662
00:57:21,320 --> 00:57:23,320 
How do you know that?

663
00:57:25,200 --> 00:57:27,120 
Oh, shit, that's true. It fits.

664
00:57:27,200 --> 00:57:29,120 
So he's a dealer.

665
00:57:29,600 --> 00:57:31,600 
Hang on a sec.

666
00:57:41,000 --> 00:57:43,120 
Now we're getting somewhere.

667
00:57:43,800 --> 00:57:45,120 
Discount Inn.

668
00:57:49,520 --> 00:57:51,400 
(activates alarm)

669
00:58:01,000 --> 00:58:02,880 
(activates alarm)

670
00:58:35,800 --> 00:58:37,320 
Yeah, OK.

671
00:58:37,400 --> 00:58:39,400 
Blonde's fine.

672
00:58:40,200 --> 00:58:42,120 
Well, that's what they say.

673
00:58:43,000 --> 00:58:45,120 
The Discount Inn. 304.

674
00:58:46,200 --> 00:58:47,880 
Leonard.

675
00:58:48,480 --> 00:58:49,880 
Well, what then?

676
00:58:50,000 --> 00:58:52,880 
We just go to bed.
You wait for me to fall asleep.

677
00:58:53,000 --> 00:58:55,120 
You go into the bathroom
and slam the door.

678
00:58:55,200 --> 00:58:57,600 
- Slam it?
- Yeah. Loud enough to wake me up.

679
00:58:57,680 --> 00:58:59,520 
- And that's it?
- That's it.

680
00:59:00,120 --> 00:59:01,000 
Ah...

681
00:59:02,320 --> 00:59:05,120 
Yeah, first I just need you
to put these things around the room.

682
00:59:07,800 --> 00:59:10,120 
Pretend they're your things
and this is your bedroom.

683
00:59:22,400 --> 00:59:27,120 
- Should I wear it?
- No, no, no. Uh, just like you took it off.

684
00:59:30,600 --> 00:59:32,320 
I don't want you to use it. I'm sorry.

685
00:59:33,880 --> 00:59:39,200 
I just mean put them around the room,
as if they were your... your things.

686
00:59:42,680 --> 00:59:44,680 
Whatever gets you off.

687
01:00:04,200 --> 01:00:06,200 
(door slams)

688
01:00:07,680 --> 01:00:10,880 
I can't blame the cops
for not taking me seriously.

689
01:00:11,000 --> 01:00:13,800 
This is a difficult condition to understand.
Look at Sammy Jankis.

690
01:00:13,880 --> 01:00:15,880 
His own wife couldn't deal with it.

691
01:00:16,000 --> 01:00:18,480 
I told you how she tried to get him
to snap out of it.

692
01:00:18,600 --> 01:00:20,880 
She came to see me at the office.
I found out all kinds of shit.

693
01:00:21,000 --> 01:00:24,320 
She told me about life with Sammy.
How she treated him.

694
01:00:24,400 --> 01:00:25,800 
Thank you for seeing me.

695
01:00:25,880 --> 01:00:28,400 
She'd get Sammy to hide food
around the house,...

696
01:00:28,480 --> 01:00:31,200 
..then she'd stop feeding him to see
if his hunger would make him remember.

697
01:00:31,320 --> 01:00:34,400 
I've taken him to a parking lot and, uh...

698
01:00:34,480 --> 01:00:37,880 
She wasn't a cruel person.
She just wanted her old Sammy back.

699
01:00:38,000 --> 01:00:40,680 
You know all about Sammy
and you've decided he's faking.

700
01:00:40,800 --> 01:00:43,400 
The company's position
isn't that Sammy's faking anything,...

701
01:00:43,520 --> 01:00:45,680 
..just that his condition
can't be shown to be...

702
01:00:45,800 --> 01:00:47,680 
I just want to know
your honest opinion about Sammy.

703
01:00:48,400 --> 01:00:51,520 
We shouldn't be talking like this
while the case is still open to appeal.

704
01:00:51,600 --> 01:00:54,680 
- I'm not appealing the decision.
- Then why are you here?

705
01:00:54,800 --> 01:01:00,480 
Try to understand, when I look at Sammy,
I don't see some... vegetable.

706
01:01:00,600 --> 01:01:03,000 
I see my same old Sammy.

707
01:01:03,800 --> 01:01:05,680 
What do you think that's like for me,...

708
01:01:05,800 --> 01:01:08,880 
..to suspect that he might be imagining
this whole problem?

709
01:01:09,000 --> 01:01:10,880 
That if I just could say the right thing,...

710
01:01:11,000 --> 01:01:15,000 
..he'd snap out of it
and go back to being normal.

711
01:01:15,400 --> 01:01:17,320 
If I...

712
01:01:18,600 --> 01:01:21,800 
If I knew that my old Sammy
were truly gone,...

713
01:01:21,880 --> 01:01:26,680 
..then I could say goodbye
and start loving this new Sammy.

714
01:01:28,480 --> 01:01:31,400 
As long as I have doubt
I can't say goodbye and move on.

715
01:01:31,520 --> 01:01:33,520 
What do you want from me?

716
01:01:33,600 --> 01:01:36,480 
I want you to forget the company
you work for, for thirty seconds...

717
01:01:36,600 --> 01:01:39,880 
..and tell me if you really believe
that Sammy's faking his condition.

718
01:01:41,200 --> 01:01:43,120 
I need to know...

719
01:01:43,320 --> 01:01:45,600 
..what you honestly believe.

720
01:01:49,800 --> 01:01:53,520 
I believe that Sammy should be physically
capable of making new memories.

721
01:02:00,400 --> 01:02:02,120 
Thank you.

722
01:02:03,600 --> 01:02:05,600 
I thought I'd helped her.

723
01:02:05,680 --> 01:02:09,520 
I thought she just needed an answer.
I didn't think it was important what it was.

724
01:02:10,120 --> 01:02:12,680 
Just that she had one to believe.

725
01:02:26,680 --> 01:02:29,400 
- A car this nice you should lock.
- Who the fuck are you?

726
01:02:29,520 --> 01:02:32,200 
- Teddy, your buddy.
- Prove it!

727
01:02:32,320 --> 01:02:35,120 
Remember Sammy?
You told me about Sammy!

728
01:02:36,800 --> 01:02:39,600 
- Jeez!
- What the fuck are you doing in my car?

729
01:02:39,680 --> 01:02:44,120 
What, your sense of humor went with the
memory? Do you know why you're here?

730
01:02:44,200 --> 01:02:46,120 
- Unfinished business.
- Lenny,...

731
01:02:46,200 --> 01:02:49,880 
..let me inform you,
your business here is very much finished.

732
01:02:50,000 --> 01:02:52,880 
- You're still here because of Natalie.
- Who's Natalie?

733
01:02:53,000 --> 01:02:56,680 
Schmuck! Whose house
do you think you just walked out of?

734
01:02:58,200 --> 01:03:02,320 
That's right, take a look at your pictures.
I bet you got one of her.

735
01:03:03,200 --> 01:03:05,520 
Oh, nice shot, Leibovitz(!)

736
01:03:06,680 --> 01:03:09,200 
You'll want to make a note.
You can't trust her.

737
01:03:09,320 --> 01:03:10,600 
